{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473842"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:15:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:15:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11513"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11513"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.09,0.09,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4144"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57723"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4144"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11513"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43182"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"2111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2112"},{"type":"tags","id":"2113"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5208"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5217"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17891"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43238"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44101"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57723"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her mother with concerns that she has not yet had her first period. Every month, the patient reports that she experiences crampy abdominal pain that usually resolves itself after two to three days, however this is never followed by vaginal bleeding. The patient is not sexually active and does not take any form of contraception. Both the patient\u2019s mother and sister experienced menarche at age 12.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination of the patient, she has normal secondary sexual characteristics of Tanner stage 5. On abdominal examination, you palpate a mass in the lower abdomen which the patient reports is non-tender. Pelvic ultrasound subsequently illustrates a distended uterus filled with \u2018fluid\u2019. Blood tests, including follicular-stimulating hormone, luteinising hormone, oestrogen, testosterone, prolactin, thyroid stimulating hormone, T4 and blood glucose, return within a normal range. A pregnancy test is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would you expect to visualise on genital examination of this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bulging membrane","Normal genital examination","Ambiguous external genitalia","Short vaginal canal","Purulent vaginal discharge"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question requires an understanding of the differentials of primary and secondary amenorrhea. Primary amenorrhea is more likely since this patient has never had a period before, ruling out secondary amenorrhoea. Primary amenorrhoea is defined as the absence of thelarche by age 13, or absence of menarche by age 15.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination you would expect to see a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebulging membrane \u003C/strong\u003Ewhich is often of a bluish colour- this is the imperforate vaginal hymen with a collection of old blood behind it. Amenorrhea associated with cyclical abdominal pain, a lower abdominal mass and normal blood tests results suggest that imperforate hymen is the most likely diagnosis. Therefore, it is unlikely that a \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal genital examination\u003C/strong\u003E will be observed in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option \u003Cstrong\u003Eambiguous external genitalia\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as this would not be seen in imperforate hymen. As described above, this patient has normally developed secondary sexual characteristics. Ambiguous genitalia would more likely be present in a condition in which sex hormone levels are abnormal. For example, 5-alpha reductase deficiency can present with ambiguous external genitalia due to failure of testosterone conversion to dihydrotestosterone (DHT).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eshort vaginal canal \u003C/strong\u003Eis not associated with an imperforate hymen. This, however, can be associated with Mullerian agenesis, another differential for primary amenorrhea. However, this is an unlikely diagnosis because clinical signs associated with this include an absent uterus, of which is not present in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe final option, \u003Cstrong\u003Epurulent vaginal discharge\u003C/strong\u003E would be associated with a sexually transmitted infection (STI). Some sexually transmitted infections affecting menarche include chlamydia. However, this is an incorrect answer because this patient is not sexually active, and is experiencing primary amenorrhoea, not secondary amenorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Imperforate hymen is a differential for primary amenorrhoea.","It is important to rule out secondary amenorrhea, including polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS), hyperprolactinaemia, diabetes, and primary ovarian failure as the cause of amenorrhea.","Other differentials for primary amenorrhoea include Turner\u2019s syndrome, Mullerian agenesis, androgen insensitivity syndrome, 5-alpha reductase deficiency and gonadal dysgenesis."],"references":["Lee KH, Hong JS, Jung HJ, Jeong HK, Moon SJ, Park WH, et al. Imperforate Hymen: A Comprehensive Systematic Review. J Clin Med. 2019;8(1):56. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6352236/ DOI: 10.3390/jcm8010056","Yoon JY, Cheon CK. Evaluation and management of amenorrhea related to congenital sex hormonal disorders. Ann Pediatr Endocrinol Metab. 2019 Sep;24(3):149-157. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6790874/ DOI: 10.6065/apem.2019.24.3.149"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43182"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11513"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43182"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-27T14:00:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-27T14:01:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4144"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57723"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"hea